 communities, explore how racial interactions and racial identity are influenced by local context, and provide evidence of what many would prefer to believe does not exist: continued anti-black prejudice among white Americans. McDermott notes that while most black-white interactions are civil and unremarkable on the surface, interactions between blacks and whites living in close proximity are characterized by continual attempts to decipher the intent behind words, actions, and gestures, and that certain situations and topics of conversation, such as crime or gender relations, often elicit racial stereotypes or negative comments. Her keen insights on the nuances of race relations will make this book essential reading for students and anyone interested in life in contemporary urban America.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aParticipant observation. 0aPrejudiceszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aSociology, UrbanzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aWhite peoplexRace identityzGeorgiazAtlanta. 0aWhite peoplexRace identityzMassachusettszBoston. 0aWorking classzGeorgiazAtlantaxAttitudes. 0aWorking classzMassachusettszBostonxAttitudes. 4aDiscrimination. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh1 aMcDermott, Monica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024809040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093969140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520939691423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520939691/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles